1948	    \item \emph{$\Gamma(X, \mathcal O_X)$ is an integral domain.} $X$ is smooth (hence reduced) and geometrically irreducible over $k$, so $X$ is in particular irreducible and reduced, hence integral. The structure sheaf of an integral scheme has integral-domain global sections (Mathlib: \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.IsIntegral}-namespace lemmas on $\Gamma$).
1949	    \item \emph{A finite integral-domain $k$-algebra over a field is a finite field extension; geometric irreducibility forces dimension $1$.} Combining (1) and (2), $\Gamma(X, \mathcal O_X)$ is a finite integral domain over the field $k$, hence is itself a field (a finite integral extension of a field is a field, Mathlib's \texttt{Algebra.IsIntegral.isField\_iff\_isField} in \texttt{Mathlib.RingTheory.IntegralClosure}), and a finite field extension of $k$. Geometric irreducibility of $X$ over $k$ propagates to $X_{\bar k} := X \times_k \Spec \bar k$ being integral and smooth proper over $\bar k$; therefore $\Gamma(X_{\bar k}, \mathcal O_{X_{\bar k}})$ is itself a finite field extension of $\bar k$, hence equals $\bar k$ (the algebraic closure has no proper finite extensions). The base-change identity $\Gamma(X, \mathcal O_X) \otimes_k \bar k \cong \Gamma(X_{\bar k}, \mathcal O_{X_{\bar k}}) = \bar k$ (from flat base change of structure-sheaf global sections, Mathlib's \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.IsBaseChange}-namespace lemmas combined with $\Gamma$-functor) forces $\dim_k \Gamma(X, \mathcal O_X) = 1$, hence $\Gamma(X, \mathcal O_X) = k \cdot 1 = \operatorname{range}(\mathtt{algebraMap}\,k\,\Gamma(X, \mathcal O_X))$.
1950	  \end{enumerate}
1951	  The three sub-facts deliver $\Gamma(X, \mathcal O_X) \cong k$, i.e.\ the displayed equality. Estimated build: $\sim 50$--$100$ LOC.
