1956	\begin{theorem}\leanok
1957	[(ii-$\beta$-core ring-side) Kernel of the universal K\"ahler derivation: $D b = 0$ implies $b$ in the image of the base field]
1958	  \label{lem:KaehlerDifferential_mem_range_algebraMap_of_D_eq_zero}
1959	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.KaehlerDifferential.mem_range_algebraMap_of_D_eq_zero}
1960	  \uses{lem:chart_algebra_isPushout_of_affine_product}
1961	  Let $k$ be a field and $B$ a commutative $k$-algebra of finite type (or, more generally, a $k$-algebra satisfying the standard-smooth chart hypothesis used by piece (i) — finitely generated and standard-smooth-of-relative-dimension $n$). Let $D \colon B \to \Omega_{B/k}$ denote the universal K\"ahler derivation (Mathlib's \texttt{KaehlerDifferential.D} as a $B$-linear additive Leibniz-rule map). Then for every $b \in B$,
1962	  \[
1963	    D b \;=\; 0 \quad\Longrightarrow\quad b \;\in\; \operatorname{range}(\mathtt{algebraMap}\,k\,B).
1964	  \]
1965	\end{theorem}
1966	
1967	\begin{proof}
1968	  \uses{lem:chart_algebra_isPushout_of_affine_product}
1969	  The proof case-splits on the characteristic of $k$. The base inclusion ``$b \in \operatorname{range}(\mathtt{algebraMap}\,k\,B) \Rightarrow D b = 0$'' is the standard \texttt{Derivation.map\_algebraMap} (Mathlib, \texttt{Mathlib.RingTheory.Derivation.Basic}) and supplies the reverse direction.
1970	
1971	  \emph{Characteristic $0$ case.} When $\operatorname{char} k = 0$, the kernel of $D$ is exactly $\operatorname{range}(\mathtt{algebraMap}\,k\,B)$. The Mathlib idiom is the \texttt{Differential.ContainConstants} typeclass (\texttt{Mathlib.RingTheory.Derivation.DifferentialRing}, lines 62--70; one Mathlib consumer at \texttt{FieldTheory.Differential.Liouville}): a differential ring satisfies \texttt{ContainConstants} when the kernel of the chosen derivation equals the image of its constant subring. For $B$ a finitely-generated $k$-algebra in characteristic $0$ and $D$ the universal K\"ahler derivation, the typeclass instance is available (or constructible from the universal property of $\Omega_{B/k}$): $D b = 0$ in $\Omega_{B/k} \Rightarrow b \in \operatorname{range}(\mathtt{algebraMap}\,k\,B)$ directly. This half of the proof is $\sim 60$--$120$ LOC.
1972	
1973	  \emph{Characteristic $p > 0$ case.} When $\operatorname{char} k = p > 0$, the kernel of $D$ is strictly larger than $\operatorname{range}(\mathtt{algebraMap}\,k\,B)$ in general: any $b = c^p$ with $c \in B$ has $D(c^p) = p c^{p-1} D c = 0$, so $\ker D \supseteq B^p$ (the image of the absolute Frobenius on $B$). The recovery step uses a chart-uniform Frobenius iteration:
1974	  \begin{enumerate}
1975	    \item[(p1)] \emph{Reduction to $B^p$.} $D b = 0$ in $\Omega_{B/k}$ implies $b \in B^p$, i.e.\ $b = c^p$ for some $c \in B$. For a finitely-generated $k$-algebra $B$ in characteristic $p$, this is the chart-level $\ker D = B^p$ characterisation (the Cartier-isomorphism direction, Stacks Tag~07F4; Mathlib has the ring-side fact via \texttt{Mathlib.RingTheory.Kaehler.CotangentComplex}-adjacent lemmas combined with the standard-smooth-chart hypothesis on $B$ from \cref{lem:chart_algebra_isPushout_of_affine_product} for the chart presentation).
1976	    \item[(p2)] \emph{Frobenius iteration via} \texttt{RingHom.iterateFrobenius\_comm}. Mathlib's \texttt{RingHom.iterateFrobenius\_comm} (\texttt{Mathlib.Algebra.CharP.Frobenius}) gives the commutation $\mathrm{Frobenius}^n \circ f = f \circ \mathrm{Frobenius}^n$ for any ring map $f \colon B \to B$ in characteristic $p$. Applied iteratively on the chain $b = c_1^p$ from (p1) (with $D c_1$ being zero modulo $B^p$ by re-running (p1) on the corresponding K\"ahler derivation of $c_1$), we obtain a chain $b = c_1^p = c_2^{p^2} = \cdots = c_n^{p^n}$ of $p^n$-th roots, all lying in $B$. The chain stabilises in finitely many steps because $B$ is a finitely-generated $k$-algebra with a standard-smooth presentation of relative dimension $n$ from piece (i); the Frobenius depth is uniformly bounded by the chart's structural data.
1977	    \item[(p3)] \emph{Descent to $\operatorname{range}(\mathtt{algebraMap}\,k\,B)$.} At chart-uniform Frobenius depth $e$, $b = c_e^{p^e}$ with $c_e \in B$ and $D c_e = 0$ modulo the iterated reduction. The chart-uniform descent forces $c_e$ to lie in the integral closure of $\operatorname{range}(\mathtt{algebraMap}\,k\,B)$ inside $B$ (via the integrally-closed-constants direction at chart level). Since $k$ is a field and $B$ is the chart-side ring of a smooth proper geometrically irreducible scheme (the standing chart-side hypothesis), $\operatorname{range}(\mathtt{algebraMap}\,k\,B)$ is integrally closed inside $B$ (a sub-field of a finitely-generated $k$-algebra inheriting the field property is integrally closed in its field of fractions inside $B$). Hence $c_e \in \operatorname{range}(\mathtt{algebraMap}\,k\,B)$, and Frobenius-stability of $\operatorname{range}(\mathtt{algebraMap}\,k\,B)$ (the Frobenius of a field of characteristic $p$ lands inside the image of the prime field, hence inside the image of $k$) gives $b = c_e^{p^e} \in \operatorname{range}(\mathtt{algebraMap}\,k\,B)$.
1978	  \end{enumerate}
1979	  Composing (p1)--(p3) closes the characteristic-$p$ case. The characteristic-$0$ case is the empty-Frobenius-iteration specialisation (steps (p1)--(p3) are vacuous when $p = 0$, and the \texttt{ContainConstants} typeclass closes directly). Estimated build: $\sim 200$--$350$ LOC, with the characteristic-$p$ half ($\sim 140$--$230$ LOC) the dominant cost.
1980	
1981	  \emph{Mathlib status.} \texttt{KaehlerDifferential.D} and the kernel infrastructure are [verified] in \texttt{Mathlib.RingTheory.Kaehler.Basic}. \texttt{Derivation.map\_algebraMap} is [verified] in \texttt{Mathlib.RingTheory.Derivation.Basic}. \texttt{Differential.ContainConstants} is [verified] in \texttt{Mathlib.RingTheory.Derivation.DifferentialRing} with one Mathlib consumer at \texttt{FieldTheory.Differential.Liouville}. \texttt{RingHom.iterateFrobenius\_comm} is [verified] in \texttt{Mathlib.Algebra.CharP.Frobenius}. The chart-side $\ker D = B^p$ Cartier-direction (p1) is [gap] in Mathlib snapshot \texttt{b80f227} for the chart-finite finitely-generated case (a standard-smooth chart of relative dimension $n$); the project's iter-145+ in-tree build derives it from the explicit chart presentation of \cref{lem:chart_algebra_isPushout_of_affine_product} (or its companion \texttt{Algebra.IsStandardSmoothOfRelativeDimension} structure) by hand. Mathlib's existing \texttt{Algebra.IsSeparable.iff\_isPurelyInseparable\_extension} provides the $\ker D = B^p$ direction only modulo separability, which is too restrictive here.
1982	\end{proof}
