1989	  Let $f, g \colon C \to A$ be two morphisms in $\Over\,(\Spec k)$ between a smooth proper geometrically irreducible curve $C$ of genus $0$ and a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme $A$ over $k$, satisfying:
1990	  \begin{itemize}
1991	    \item $\mathrm df = \mathrm dg$ as morphisms of $\mathcal O_C$-modules $f^{*}\,\Omega_{A/k} \to \Omega_{C/k}$ (equivalently, the difference $\mathrm d(\mu \circ \langle f, \iota \circ g \rangle) = \mathrm df - \mathrm dg = 0$ vanishes, where $\mu$ and $\iota$ are the multiplication and inversion of $A$ supplied by the $\GrpObj A$ structure);
1992	    \item $f$ and $g$ agree on a non-empty open subset $U \subseteq C$, i.e.\ $U.\iota \circ f|_{U} = U.\iota \circ g|_{U}$ as scheme morphisms $U \to A$.
1993	  \end{itemize}
1994	  Then $f = g$ as morphisms in $\Over\,(\Spec k)$.
1995	
1996	  In the specialisation $g := c$ the constant morphism at $\eta_A \in A(k)$ (with $\mathrm dc = 0$ automatically because $c$ factors through $\Spec k$, and the agreement on $U$ supplied by promoting the pointing hypothesis $f(p) = \eta_A$ to a chart around $p$ via continuity), this delivers the C.2.d conclusion of \cref{thm:rigidity_over_kbar}: $f$ equals the constant morphism at $\eta_A$.
1997	\end{theorem}

